{"id":"1901.06452","submitter":"Ronan Keane","authors":"Ronan Keane and H. Oliver Gao","title":"Fast Calibration of Car Following models to Trajectory data using the\n  Adjoint Method","comments":"accepted to transportation science","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1287/trsc.2020.1027","report-no":null,"categories":"cs.SY","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Before a car-following model can be applied in practice, it must first be\nvalidated against real data in a process known as calibration. This paper\ndiscusses the formulation of calibration as an optimization problem, and\ncompares different algorithms for its solution. The optimization consists of an\narbitrary car following model, posed as either an ordinary or delay\ndifferential equation, being calibrated to an arbitrary source of trajectory\ndata which may include lane changes. Typically, the calibration problem is\nsolved using gradient free optimization. In this work, the gradient of the\noptimization problem is derived analytically using the adjoint method. The\ncomputational cost of the adjoint method does not scale with the number of\nmodel parameters, which makes it more efficient than evaluating the gradient\nnumerically using finite differences. Numerical results are presented which\nshow that quasi-newton algorithms using the adjoint method are significantly\nfaster than a genetic algorithm, and also achieve slightly better accuracy of\nthe calibrated model.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 19 Jan 2019 01:31:58 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 3 Apr 2019 03:42:37 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 21 Sep 2020 07:14:42 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-03-16"}
