{"id":"1901.08892","submitter":"John V. Corbett","authors":"John V Corbett","title":"Quantum dynamics is infinitesimal qr-number dynamics","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.gen-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The Heisenberg equations of motion for a quantum particle of mass $m$ are\ndeduced from the infinitesimal qr-number equations of motion for the particle.\nThe infinitesimal qr-number equations, and hence the standard quantum\nmechanical equations, are related to the qr-number equations in much the same\nway as the equations of geometric optics are related to those of wave optics.\nThe qr-number equations of motion for a quantum particle of mass $m$ describe\nthe motion of a lump, given by on open set in the qr-number space of the\nparticle, while the infinitesimal qr-number equations describe the motion of a\npoint-like particle. The qr-number equations of motion are the Hamiltonian\nequations of motion for a classical particle of mass $m$ expressed in\nqr-numbers. The proof requires that the particle's position operators have only\ncontinuous spectrum and the force functions are smooth.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 19 Jan 2019 00:20:31 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-01-28"}
